s that employed 22,000 men and women at its heyday, the Department operated a "machine" with myriad moving parts. The first part of the book portrays the people who kept it running, from technical experts to menial servants, and scrutinises the paper trails they left behind. Part two uncovers the working principles of the machine by following the production chains of some of its most splendid products: gilded statues, jade, porcelain, and textiles. Part three tackles the most complex task of all, managing living organisms in nature, including lotus plants grown in imperial ponds in Beijing, fresh medicines sourced from disparate regions, and tribute elephants from Southeast Asia.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0https://www.aup.nl/en/publish/open-access  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 4aArt and Material Culture. 4aAsian Studies. 4aEast Asia and North East Asia. 4aHealth and Medicine. 4aHistory. 4aScience and Technology. 7aHISTORY / Asia / China.2bisacsh  aChina, Qing Court, Material culture, Science & technology, Imperial Household Department.1 aAkcetin, Elif, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBae, Kyoungjin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChen, Kai Jun, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChen, Kai Jun, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aGuan, Xueling, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJun Chen, Kai, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKo, Dorothy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKo, Dorothy, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aLai, Hui-min, econtributor.